    },
    "Find Previous" : {

    },
    "Find…" : {

    },
    "Five Hebrew letters have special forms when they appear at the end of a word: Kaf (כ→ך), Mem (מ→ם), Nun (נ→ן), Pe (פ→ף), and Tsadi (צ→ץ). These are called sofit (final) letters." : {

    },
    "Fix Hebrew in non-RTL software" : {

    },
    "Fix with reversal" : {

    },
    "Fixing Adobe Apps (Tomech Ivrit)" : {

    },
    "Found in 1993 in northern Israel, the Tel Dan Stele is a 9th-century BCE Aramaic inscription that contains the earliest known reference to the “House of David” outside the Bible. While written in Aramaic, it uses a script closely related to Paleo-Hebrew and is a landmark find for biblical archaeology." : {

    },
    "Gematria" : {
      "localizations" : {
        "he" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "גימטריה"
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "Gematria has been used for thousands of years in Jewish biblical interpretation (hermeneutics). Words or phrases with equal numerical values are considered to have a hidden connection. For example, the Hebrew word for “life” (חי) equals 18, which is why 18 is considered a lucky number in Jewish tradition." : {

    },
    "Gematria is the practice of assigning numerical values to Hebrew letters and calculating the sum of a word or phrase. Each of the 22 Hebrew letters has a fixed value: Aleph=1, Bet=2, Gimel=3, and so on up to Tav=400." : {

    },
